{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519639","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519639"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:14:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:14:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13057"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13057","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13057"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.04,0.07,0.69,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5494"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98958"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5494","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5494"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13057"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81350"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"256"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4046"},{"type":"tags","id":"9270"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26419"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33962"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98958","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/98958"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 76-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-month history of anorexia and weight loss. She reports her skin and eyes have become yellow over the past two weeks. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is a non-smoker and drinks minimal alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears jaundiced but not in distress. Her vital signs are within normal limits. Her abdomen is soft and non-tender with no palpable masses. A CT scan is performed (Image 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cirrhosis","Renal cell carcinoma","Carcinoma of the gastric antrum","Carcinoma of the pancreas","Gastrointestinal stromal tumour"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation of painless jaundice, anorexia, and weight loss in an elderly patient, combined with CT findings of biliary tract dilatation, is highly suggestive of pancreatic cancer. The tumour can be seen on the CT, together with a distended gallbladder (Image). Approximately 70% of pancreatic cancers occur in the head of the pancreas, where they can cause obstruction of the common bile duct leading to obstructive jaundice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoma of the pancreas\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents in elderly patients with the classic triad of painless jaundice, weight loss, and anorexia. CT findings often show a pancreatic mass (if visible) and biliary dilatation due to obstruction of the common bile duct.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECirrhosis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause jaundice but would typically have other features such as ascites, spider naevi, and portal hypertension. The biliary system would not be dilated on imaging as the jaundice is hepatocellular rather than obstructive in nature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with haematuria, loin pain, and a palpable mass. While it can cause weight loss, it would not cause biliary obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoma of the gastric antrum\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with early satiety, epigastric pain, and vomiting. While it can cause weight loss and anorexia, it would not typically cause biliary obstruction unless very advanced.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastrointestinal stromal tumour\u003C/strong\u003E most commonly occurs in the stomach and small intestine. While it can cause weight loss and anorexia, it would rarely cause biliary obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most pancreatic cancers are found in the head of the gland and 50% of these will present with jaundice.","The classic triad of pancreatic cancer is painless jaundice, weight loss, and anorexia.","CT findings of pancreatic cancer may include biliary dilatation, pancreatic mass, and double duct sign (dilated bile and pancreatic ducts)."],"references":["Park W, Chawla A, O\u0027Reilly EM. Pancreatic Cancer A Review. JAMA 2021; 326:851-62. Available at: https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/article-abstract/2783817"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81350"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13057"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21845"},{"type":"media","id":"21846"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21847"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21845","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21845"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/VS3BteuovuHyTb7lziX8cPjwmginta.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/VS3BteuovuHyTb7lziX8cPjwmginta.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":461,"height":461}},{"type":"media","id":"21846","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21846"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/uZGOTT61KVnyawZz8Ot1XpP09Vsisw.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/uZGOTT61KVnyawZz8Ot1XpP09Vsisw.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":461,"height":461}},{"type":"med